The Constitutional Design of a Multiplanetary Civilization: Navigating Transparency and Autonomy in Sensor-Rich, Resource-Constrained Settlements

A Doctoral Dissertation


---

Abstract

This dissertation examines the socio-technical challenges of establishing a self-sustaining human settlement on Mars via reusable launch architectures and pervasive sensor networks. The primary transition—from Bootstrapping (transport/infrastructure) to Stabilization (governance under scarcity and isolation)—creates an irreducible dilemma: the same transparency that prevents commons tragedies enables risks of digital overreach or psychological strain.

Employing the novel Recursive Blueprint Method (RBM), the analysis evolves conceptual models across four generations, culminating in a Direct Ledger Democracy hybrid: an immutable resource ledger enforces democratically chosen allocation rules (via direct votes on short, sunsetting proposals), with transparency purpose-limited to commons, strong obfuscation rights for private spheres, and built-in safeguards against institutional drift. This framework aligns sensor-derived visibility with principles of maximal individual autonomy and minimal coercion, transforming the settlement's cyber-physical constitution (Lex Machina) into a tool subservient to citizen choice rather than its defining feature.

The research demonstrates that viability emerges not from technology alone but from pre-launch constitutional prototyping that balances survival imperatives with enduring liberty. Implications extend to terrestrial transparent societies and establish exo-political design as a critical discipline for humanity's multiplanetary future.

Keywords: Mars Settlement, Direct Democracy, Resource Commons, Symmetrical Transparency, Algorithmic Governance, Recursive Blueprint Method, Astrosociology, Cyber-Physical Constitutions

